column17: F1000 AWS buckets, very easy to use, unfortunately not always up to date or the most curated version. In general, anything that allows for simple queries and let's me download raw data in an automated way is great.
ConnectomeDB, Strongly Agree; AWS Public Datasets, Agree
OpenfMRI - very positive (the MAIN database for fMRI researchers!)
Neurosynth. It was a straightforward process downloading scans based off search terms.
HCP / BALSA, not a standard repository, still very important and quite easy to download from.

LONI - quite intuitive search of files, but selection of files of interest for download can be quite frustrating.

NITRC - not very intuitive for searching but quite easy downloading.
